ndependent category, anchoring it firmly within the religious world view. Tracing Assur's cultural interaction with the south on the one hand, and with the Syro-Anatolian horizon on the other, this volume articulates a "northern" cultural discourse that, even while interacting with southern Mesopotamian tradition, managed to maintain its own identity. It also follows the development of tropes and iconic images from the first city state of Uruk and their mouvance between myth, image, and royal inscription, historiography and myth, and myth and ritual, suggesting that, with the help of scholars, key royal figures were responsible for introducing new directions for the ideological discourse and for promoting new forms of historiography.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aIdeologyxAssyria. 0aIdeologyzAssyria. 0aMonarchyxAssyria. 0aMonarchyzAssyria. 4aAssyria. 4aIdeology. 4aReligion. 4aideology. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2015z9783110438604oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97816145195460 cprintz978161451482440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161451426840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781614514268423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781614514268.jpg  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2015  aZDB-23-DGGb2015